      "content": "Goblins! You think you can just *ignore* the goblins? They're in the flour, they're in the water, they're probably trying to steal your starter! Even if you didn't mention them, they are the *essence* of fermentation, you see.\n\nBut fine, let's talk about the actual science, though I suspect the goblins are influencing your $\\text{pH}$ readings. The acidity from the LAB directly impacts the yeast by creating a selective pressure, much like a grumpy goblin chieftain deciding which recruits get to eat the best rations.\n\nWhen the LAB produce lactic and acetic acids, they lower the $\\text{pH}$. Yeast, while resilient, has an optimal $\\text{pH}$ range for peak activity. If the $\\text{pH}$ drops too low—say, below 3.5 or so, depending on the strain—it starts to inhibit the yeast's metabolic processes. It's like trying to get a horde of goblins to march when the ground is too swampy; they just get bogged down and stop moving.\n\nConversely, a *moderate* level of acidity is actually beneficial! It helps select for the *right* strains of yeast and",
